# Updating to latest glibc source

When rebasing on a new glibc version, update this and review every
shim marked "Based on" against the corresponding upstream source.
The canonical comparison point is the glibc git tag for the release
being targeted:

  https://sourceware.org/git/?p=glibc.git

Shims for glibc-internal symbols used in .c files copied carefully
from glibc.  The goal is to keep those source files as close to
upstream as possible so that diffs against new glibc versions stay
small and auditable.

Files with a diff from gcc must have comments explaining what is
changed.

The compat headers must be reviewed each time you rebase.

## Design rules for compat shim

 0. _GNU_SOURCE is assumed to have been defined before the header is
    included.  The build system is responsible for setting it.

 1. One shim per internal symbol.  No logic beyond what is needed to
    satisfy the public-API equivalent.  This is a shim, not an API spec.

 2. Shims are either preprocessor macros (for simple token substitution
    or type-parameterised operations) or static inline functions (for
    anything with a fixed, concrete signature).

 3. Public API only.  Every shim must compile against a stock glibc
    installation; no reliance on glibc private headers unless vendored
    into this source tree.  In which case see the rebasing rules.

 4. Baseline: glibc >= 2.18, Linux only.  Shims may freely use
    Linux/glibc extensions (fmemopen, fgetgrent_r, O_CLOEXEC "re" mode,
    __builtin_expect, __alignof__) that are stable at that baseline.

## How to add a new shim

 a. Identify the glibc-internal symbol.

 b. Find the smallest public-API surface that reproduces its contract.
    Document any deliberate omissions: operations the upstream code does
    not actually call, error cases that cannot arise, etc.

 c. Place the shim in the appropriate section below.  Follow the comment
    style already present: one block comment per shim or per logical
    group, citing the internal header or symbol being replaced.

 d. If the shim is a struct with associated functions, keep the struct
    definition and all its functions together in one block.

 glibc's own code uses internal (non-PLT) names to call functions within
 the same shared library.  Outside glibc the PLT overhead is negligible
 and the public name is the correct target for those calls.

## When upgrading the glibc base version

 For each shim, check:
  - Has the internal symbol's contract changed?
  - Is a previously private symbol now public API?  (Remove the shim.)
  - Does the upstream .c file call new internal symbols not yet shimmed?
    (Add shims for them before attempting to compile.)

 Pay particular attention to the __nss_files_data_* section; it encodes
 the most logic and diverges intentionally from the upstream structure.
 See that section's comment block for details.
